snippet.textDisplay:
Hold on, if the understanding is there that carrying a massive mass of batteries around wastes energy in itself, just carrying those batteries around while they discharge, and the concept exists for adding extra batteries for longer journeys, why don’t we just exchange small battery packs as and when we need them at the same proposed service stations instead of worrying about charging facilities at home or en route? (And have the smallest possible vehicles at the same time). Why do we need something the size of one and a half Range Rovers except for vanity?
We never used to worry about my donkey being bigger than your donkey. Any donkey would do, as long as it got you to where you wanted to go, or you could exchange it en route for another donkey to get you further. Same principle.

snippet.textDisplay:
As the power density of batteries increases, this kind of expensive to produce transforming to have more space for batteries car concept loses its sense, this transformation is necessary only because currently you can't pack too many batteries into a bottom of a compact city viable car, but this will likely not be an issue in the decade or so. Another issue is that even if in principle it is an interesting idea for such a system to proliferate, it would require some standardized platform across car producers to be really popular similar to standardized car chargers, Reanult could hardly afford to have such docking station in every city on its own and this idea would not be popular without high-density infrastructure, while other companies will likely be more interested in selling plug-in hybrids performing the same role or quick-charging cars with big batteries for higher profit margins...
If purpose of this car was just to generate interest in such technology, that's perfectly fine, because if such idea ever proliferate it will be without expensive and heavier than normal transforming anyway, though cost of necessary infrastructure requiring cooperation between multiple companies likely means, that carmakers will most likely prefer solution already developed in vehicles like BMW i3 REX for years to come if they would want small battery car with optional long-range without too much weight penalty, at least as long as there is still dense network of gas stations, which of course may not be the case several decades later...

snippet.textDisplay:
Genius, pure genius. This is 'the French' doing what they do best; brilliant, different - and proud to be so - design. Not for the narrow minded or faint hearted but those who think for themselves perhaps.
This company really are the innovators in the mass EV market it seems. If they keep improving on the build quality and reliability there are good times ahead. Be great to see some of these concepts make it to production.
With VW having been somewhat forced to change their behaviour - and their upcoming EV's - things are looking good.
The issue of price reductions will need to be addressed but that will come with time, and sooner than we thought by the looks of things.

snippet.textDisplay: Exactly the issue I have.  I use my (at the moment, petrol) car for a very small daily commute, shopping and visiting friends, family, etc.  The longest of these journeys is approx 30 miles round-trip, so to me, perfect for an EV, like the Leaf or MG ZSEV.  The fly in the ointment is our once or twice a year trip to France for holidays and visiting my wife's family.  Even getting to Dover in a Leaf or ZSEV would require a stop for recharge and there's another approx 400 miles on the other side of the channel, so would be a military operation and my wife is NOT keen!  This type of on-demand range extension would be perfect!

snippet.textDisplay: Thinking outside the box is a French speciality. You cannot complete an engineering degree here without taking a philosophy course with it. Often this way of thinking ends up with the French falling flat on their faces but it has produced revolutionary designs from the Traction Avant of the 1930’s, through the 2CV and DS...and in the world of railways and architecture, there is a lot to inspire here and for others to aspire to. In 2017 I played a part in setting up a conference at Warwick University on energy storage technology. Many of the big energy companies and car companies were there. At that conference Renault talked about the energy subsidiary they had just set up..the presenter said ‘with 30,000 Zoe’s on the road in France we have the equivalent of a 1Gw power station on wheels'. The energy industry is 5 times the size of the car industry and you can imagine how traditional dealers can see their post-sales revenue draining away with the reduced maintenance work required on EVs..using the real estate of car dealers to expand EV battery capacity and provide grid storage would make sense. It probably won’t come to anything but if people can see the $...who knows.

snippet.textDisplay: The swappable battery concept is great.  Not new, but great.  The rest? Meh. You can't use the analogy of aircraft wings to support the silly sliding mechanism.  The environment on roads is very different with crud being caught up in all those slidey bits.  Much of the rest is typical concept fluff.  Of course, the infrastructure to support all these battery replacements would be huge and probably uneconomic for a single vendor.  The only sustainable solution would be to have standard battery packs for all EVs which would be swappable.  I wonder if that will ever happen?
